      <!-- Section 1 -->
      <section id="what-is-entity-optimisation" class="anchor-top prose-dark mb-16">
        <h2>What Entity Optimisation Is</h2>

        <p>
          <strong>Entity optimisation is the discipline of ensuring your brand exists as a clearly defined, consistently described, and verifiably real object within the knowledge structures that AI systems use to understand the world.</strong>
          It is not a content strategy. It is not a link-building exercise. It is the foundational work that determines whether AI systems
          can identify your brand at all — and whether what they say about it is accurate.
        </p>

        <p>
          In the context of <a href="/generative-engine-optimisation/">generative engine optimisation</a>, an entity is a distinct real-world object:
          an organisation, product, person, place, or concept that can be uniquely identified with a stable set of attributes. AI systems do not
          process queries as strings of words. They process them as questions about entities. When a user asks "what are the best accounting tools for
          UK freelancers?", the AI resolves "accounting tools" to a set of known product entities, filters them by "UK" and "freelancers" attributes,
          and generates a response naming those entities.
        </p>

        <p>
          The brands that appear in that response are not there because they have the most backlinks, the highest domain authority, or the best-optimised
          landing pages. They are there because they exist as well-defined, correctly classified entities in the knowledge structures the AI consulted.
          Entity optimisation is the work that puts — and keeps — your brand in those structures.
        </p>

        <h3>Why Entity Optimisation Is Different from Traditional SEO</h3>

        <p>
          Traditional SEO operates on the keyword layer: optimise your content to match the words users type into search boxes.
          Entity optimisation operates on the semantic layer: ensure AI systems understand what your organisation is, what it does,
          who it serves, and how it relates to other entities in your category.
        </p>

        <p>
          A brand can hold the number-one organic position for every relevant keyword in its category and still generate poor AI citations —
          because AI visibility is determined by entity graph signals, not keyword relevance scores. Conversely, a brand with modest organic
          rankings but strong entity authority may be consistently cited by ChatGPT, Perplexity, and Google AI Overviews, because its entity
          record is clear and its attributes are well-corroborated.
        </p>

        <p>
          This does not make traditional SEO irrelevant — strong domain authority and high-quality content remain inputs into RAG retrieval.
          But entity optimisation is the layer that ensures those inputs translate into accurate, consistent AI citations rather than
          omissions or misrepresentations.
        </p>
      </section>

      <!-- Section 2 -->
      <section id="how-ai-understands-entities" class="anchor-top prose-dark mb-16">
        <h2>How AI Systems Understand Entities</h2>

        <p>
          <strong>AI systems build their understanding of entities from three distinct sources: parametric knowledge encoded during training, structured knowledge graphs queried at inference time, and retrieved documents processed in real time.</strong>
          Each source contributes differently to AI entity understanding, and each requires a different optimisation approach.
        </p>

        <h3>Parametric Entity Knowledge</h3>

        <p>
          When a large language model is trained, it processes billions of documents and encodes statistical patterns about entities into its weights.
          An organisation mentioned thousands of times in authoritative documents — Wikipedia articles, news coverage, research papers,
          industry publications — will have a rich parametric representation. The model will be able to describe it accurately, classify it correctly,
          and associate it with the right topics and attributes, drawing purely on learned patterns.
        </p>

        <p>
          An organisation mentioned infrequently, inconsistently, or only in low-authority sources will have sparse or noisy parametric representation.
          The model may confuse it with similarly named entities, describe it inaccurately, or simply not know enough about it to cite it confidently.
          Improving parametric representation requires a long-term strategy: building editorial presence in high-authority publications that feed
          training corpora, establishing knowledge base entries, and ensuring consistent entity descriptions across every source.
        </p>

        <h3>Knowledge Graph Entity Resolution</h3>

        <p>
          Many AI systems — particularly Google AI Overviews and Copilot — query structured knowledge graphs during inference to resolve entity
          attributes. When a query involves a brand name, the system looks up that entity in Google's Knowledge Graph, Wikidata, or similar
          structured databases to retrieve canonical attributes: official name, category, website, description, and related entities.
        </p>

        <p>
          Brands with a Knowledge Graph entry and a Wikidata Q-number are resolved cleanly and described using verified, up-to-date attributes.
          Brands without these entries are described from training data alone — which may be outdated, sparse, or inaccurate. For in-depth
          guidance on building this infrastructure, see our
          <a href="/knowledge-graph-optimisation/">knowledge graph optimisation</a> guide.
        </p>

        <h3>Retrieval-Augmented Entity Understanding</h3>

        <p>
          RAG-based systems like Perplexity retrieve live web content when processing queries. The structured data on your own pages —
          Organisation schema, Article schema, FAQPage schema — provides machine-readable entity signals that help the retrieval system
          classify your content correctly. A page with well-implemented <a href="/schema-markup-ai/">schema markup</a> is easier for a
          RAG system to parse and attribute to the correct entity.
        </p>
      </section>

      <!-- Section 3 -->
      <section id="entity-authority-pillars" class="anchor-top mb-16">
        <div class="prose-dark">
          <h2>The Four Pillars of Entity Authority</h2>
          <p>
            <strong>Entity authority is the aggregate confidence with which AI systems recognise and describe your brand correctly.</strong>
            It is built through four parallel workstreams, each of which reinforces the others. Strong performance across all four
            produces robust, compound entity authority that is difficult for competitors to displace.
          </p>
        </div>

        <div class="mt-8 space-y-6">

          <div class="card p-6">
            <h3 class="font-display text-base font-semibold text-[var(--accent)]">Pillar 1: On-Site Structured Data</h3>
            <p class="mt-3 text-sm leading-relaxed text-ink-300">
              Your website is the primary authoritative source for your brand's entity record. A complete Organisation schema
              in JSON-LD format — with legal name, trading name, description, founding date, industry classification, logo,
              contact details, and a comprehensive <code>sameAs</code> array — gives AI systems a structured, machine-readable
              declaration of your entity attributes. This is the baseline. Without it, every other entity signal is working
              without a clear reference point. See our <a href="/schema-markup-ai/" class="text-[var(--accent)] border-b border-[var(--accent)]/35 hover:border-[var(--accent)] transition">schema markup guide</a>
              for complete implementation patterns.
            </p>
          </div>

          <div class="card p-6">
            <h3 class="font-display text-base font-semibold text-[var(--accent)]">Pillar 2: Third-Party Knowledge Base Presence</h3>
            <p class="mt-3 text-sm leading-relaxed text-ink-300">
              AI systems cross-reference your entity record against external knowledge bases to verify and enrich their understanding.
              The priority targets are: Wikidata (provides a unique Q-number identifier), Wikipedia (heavily represented in training
              corpora), Google Business Profile (direct input to Google AI systems), Crunchbase (feeds technology and startup AI pipelines),
              and Companies House (UK entity verification). For each, ensure the entity attributes precisely match your canonical record.
              Detailed implementation guidance is in our
              <a href="/knowledge-graph-optimisation/" class="text-[var(--accent)] border-b border-[var(--accent)]/35 hover:border-[var(--accent)] transition">knowledge graph optimisation</a> guide.
            </p>
          </div>

          <div class="card p-6">
            <h3 class="font-display text-base font-semibold text-[var(--accent)]">Pillar 3: Cross-Platform Entity Consistency</h3>
            <p class="mt-3 text-sm leading-relaxed text-ink-300">
              AI systems aggregate entity signals from multiple sources. When those sources are consistent — same name,
              same description, same founding date, same category classification — the AI can confidently reconcile them
              to a single entity record. When they are inconsistent, the AI faces disambiguation uncertainty and resolves
              conservatively: either omitting the brand from its response or generating an averaged, hedged description
              that may not accurately represent your brand. Consistency is a maintenance discipline, not a one-time task.
              Entity data changes — names, addresses, product lines — must be propagated to all sources systematically.
            </p>
          </div>

          <div class="card p-6">
            <h3 class="font-display text-base font-semibold text-[var(--accent)]">Pillar 4: Editorial Corroboration</h3>
            <p class="mt-3 text-sm leading-relaxed text-ink-300">
              External editorial references — mentions in industry publications, coverage in news outlets, citations in research
              papers — serve as third-party corroboration that your entity is real, active, and correctly described.
              AI training pipelines weight authoritative editorial sources highly. A brand mentioned and described consistently
              in ten high-authority publications builds parametric entity authority that is absorbed into model weights and
              persists across training cycles. Digital PR, thought leadership contributions, and analyst relations are all
              entity optimisation activities as much as they are brand awareness activities.
            </p>
          </div>

        </div>

        <div class="prose-dark mt-8">
          <p>
            These four pillars align with the entity authority component of the broader
            <a href="/ai-brand-visibility/">AI brand visibility</a> framework. Entity authority is the foundational pillar —
            it enables and amplifies the other four (content citability, structured data, source credibility, and cross-platform presence).
            Investing in entity optimisation first is the highest-ROI sequencing decision for most brands starting a GEO programme.
          </p>
          <p>
            For brands wanting to immediately signal their entity data to AI crawlers without waiting for knowledge base propagation,
            deploying an <a href="/llms-txt/">llms.txt file</a> provides a curated machine-readable summary that AI systems
            can access directly.
          </p>
        </div>
      </section>

