      <section id="entity-audit" class="anchor-top prose-dark mb-16">
        <h2>Running an Entity Audit</h2>

        <p>
          <strong>An entity audit is the mandatory first step of any entity optimisation programme — it maps every inconsistency between your canonical entity record and how your brand is described across external sources.</strong>
          Without an audit, optimisation effort is often misdirected at symptoms rather than root causes.
        </p>

        <h3>Step 1: Define Your Canonical Entity Record</h3>

        <p>
          Before auditing external sources, establish the correct authoritative record for your organisation. This canonical record should include:
          legal name (exact Companies House / Companies Register spelling), trading name (if different), founding date,
          registered address, primary industry classification, official description (one clear sentence), official website URL,
          and a list of all products or services with their correct names. Every external source will be audited against this canonical record.
        </p>

        <h3>Step 2: Inventory All External Entity Records</h3>

        <p>
          Compile a complete list of every external source that describes your organisation: Google Business Profile, Wikidata,
          Wikipedia, LinkedIn company page, Crunchbase, Companies House, industry directories, social media profiles,
          review platforms (Trustpilot, G2, Capterra), press mentions with entity descriptions, and any data aggregators
          (Dun &amp; Bradstreet, Bureau van Dijk for enterprise brands). The goal is comprehensive coverage — every source that
          AI training pipelines and knowledge graph systems might consult.
        </p>

        <h3>Step 3: Identify Inconsistencies</h3>

        <p>
          Compare each external record against your canonical entity record. Common inconsistencies include: trading name
          vs legal name confusion, outdated descriptions from an earlier business phase, wrong industry classifications,
          inconsistent founding dates (especially if the company has rebranded or restructured), and URL variations
          pointing to old domains or HTTP rather than HTTPS. Document every inconsistency, the source, and the specific
          attribute affected.
        </p>

        <h3>Step 4: Prioritise Remediation</h3>

        <p>
          Prioritise remediation by the source's authority and AI feed status. Google Business Profile, Wikidata, Wikipedia,
          and LinkedIn should be corrected first — they are directly consumed by AI systems. Industry directories and
          secondary sources follow. For sources you cannot directly edit, outreach to the publisher is the remediation path.
          Track every correction and verify it has propagated before marking it resolved.
        </p>

        <p>
          Our <a href="/geo-services/#entity-optimisation">entity optimisation service</a> covers the full audit and remediation process
          across more than twenty data sources, with ongoing monitoring to catch new inconsistencies as they emerge.
        </p>
